\begin{scripture}[][book=Mark, extraskip=0pt, chapter/hide, verse/hide, heading/show=false]
  \heading{Jesus Heals a Man With Leprosy}

  \vs{40}A man with leprosy came to him and begged him on his knees, ‘If you
  are willing, you can make me clean.’

  \vs{41}Jesus was indignant. He reached out his hand and touched the man. ‘I
  am willing,’ he said. ‘Be clean!’ \vs{42}Immediately the leprosy left him and
  he was cleansed.

  \vs{43}Jesus sent him away at once with a strong warning: \vs{44}‘See that
  you don’t tell this to anyone. But go, show yourself to the priest and offer
  the sacrifices that Moses commanded for your cleansing, as a testimony to
  them.’ \vs{45}Instead he went out and began to talk freely, spreading the
  news. As a result, Jesus could no longer enter a town openly but stayed
  outside in lonely places. Yet the people still came to him from everywhere.

  \extraskip

  \heading{Jesus Forgives and Heals a Paralysed Man}

  \ch{2}A few days later, when Jesus again entered Capernaum, the people heard
  that he had come home. \vs{2}They gathered in such large numbers that there
  was no room left, not even outside the door, and he preached the word to
  them. \vs{3}Some men came, bringing to him a paralysed man, carried by four
  of them. \vs{4}Since they could not get him to Jesus because of the crowd,
  they made an opening in the roof above Jesus by digging through it and then
  lowered the mat the man was lying on. \vs{5}When Jesus saw their faith, he
  said to the paralysed man, ‘Son, your sins are forgiven.’

  \vs{6}Now some teachers of the law were sitting there, thinking to
  themselves, \vs{7}‘Why does this fellow talk like that? He’s blaspheming! Who
  can forgive sins but God alone?’

  \vs{8}Immediately Jesus knew in his spirit that this was what they were
  thinking in their hearts, and he said to them, ‘Why are you thinking these
  things? \vs{9}Which is easier: to say to this paralysed man, “Your sins are
  forgiven,” or to say, “Get up, take your mat and walk”? \vs{10}But I want you
  to know that the Son of Man has authority on earth to forgive sins.’ So he
  said to the man, \vs{11}‘I tell you, get up, take your mat and go home.’
  \vs{12}He got up, took his mat and walked out in full view of them all. This
  amazed everyone and they praised God, saying, ‘We have never seen anything
  like this!’
\end{scripture}

\clearpage

\vspace*{14cm}

\begin{scripture}[][book=1 Corinthians, chapter=10, extraskip=0pt, chapter/hide, verse/hide, heading/show=false]
  \heading{The believer’s freedom}

  \vs{23}‘I have the right to do anything,’ you say – but not everything is
  beneficial. ‘I have the right to do anything’– but not everything is
  constructive. \vs{24}No one should seek their own good, but the good of
  others.

  \vs{25}Eat anything sold in the meat market without raising questions of
  conscience, \vs{26}for, ‘The earth is the Lord’s, and everything in it.’

  \vs{27}If an unbeliever invites you to a meal and you want to go, eat
  whatever is put before you without raising questions of conscience.
  \vs{28}But if someone says to you, ‘This has been offered in sacrifice,’
  then do not eat it, both for the sake of the one who told you and for the
  sake of conscience. \vs{29}I am referring to the other person’s conscience,
  not yours. For why is my freedom being judged by another’s conscience?
  \vs{30}If I take part in the meal with thankfulness, why am I denounced
  because of something I thank God for?

  \begin{midparachap}
    \vs{31}So whether you eat or drink or whatever you do, do it all for the
    glory of God. \vs{32}Do not cause anyone to stumble, whether Jews, Greeks
    or the church of God – \vs{33}even as I try to please everyone in every
    way.  For I am not seeking my own good but the good of many, so that they
    may be saved. \ch{11}Follow my example, as I follow the example of Christ.
  \end{midparachap}
  
  \heading{On covering the head in worship}

  \vs{2}I praise you for remembering me in everything and for holding to the
  traditions just as I passed them on to you. \vs{3}But I want you to realise
  that the head of every man is Christ, and the head of the woman is man, and
  the head of Christ is God. \vs{4}Every man who prays or prophesies with his
  head covered dishonours his head. \vs{5}But every woman who prays or
  prophesies with her head uncovered dishonours her head – it is the same as
  having her head shaved. \vs{6}For if a woman does not cover her head, she
  might as well have her hair cut off; but if it is a disgrace for a woman to
  have her hair cut off or her head shaved, then she should cover her head.
\end{scripture}
